  "prompt": "Why does water spread grease and oil fires?",
  "response": "Water should not be used to extinguish grease and oil fires because it can actually make the situation worse. When water is poured onto a burning grease or oil fire, it can spread the fire for several reasons:\n\n1. **Density**: Water is denser than most oils. When water is added to burning grease or oil, it sinks to the bottom of the flames. If the oil is hot enough, the water can instantly turn to steam, which expands rapidly and causes the burning oil to splatter and spread.\n\n2. **Steam Explosion**: The rapid conversion of water to steam creates a forceful explosion of steam that can propel burning oil droplets into the air, igniting further areas and spreading the fire.\n\n3. **Increased Flammability**: As the burning oil is splattered or aerosolized by the steam explosion, it increases the surface area of the burning material, allowing more fuel to burn and leading to a larger fire.\n\nFor these reasons, it is crucial to use appropriate extinguishing agents such as a Class K fire extinguisher (for kitchen fires involving cooking oils and fats) or dry chemical extinguishers which can safely smother a grease or oil fire without spreading it. Additionally, using a lid to cover the burning pot or pan can help to suffocate the fire by cutting off its oxygen supply.",
